[3] Burma (Myanmar)
Date: Fri 10 Aug 2007
Source: Mizzima News [edited]
<http://www.mizzima.com/MizzimaNews/News/2007/Aug/28-Aug-2007.html>

With 98 deaths and more than 8000 reported cases of dengue fever
between January and July 2007, Burma is currently facing an 'unusual
occurrence' of the disease said the World Health Organization. It
warned that it is likely to continue until the end of August [2007].
Dr. Chusak, dengue prevention and control of the WHO's Southeast Asia
Regional Office, said with heavy rainfall, the occurrence of the
fever has increased to 8445 reported cases from 6711 cases last year
[2006]. It is likely to continue until the end of August or even
September [2007].
"The peak season is usually August in Burma but according to what we
can see, it is likely to extend up to September [2007]," Dr. Chusak,
who is also coordinator of communicable disease control for WHO's
SEARO, told Mizzima.
Heavy rainfall in Burma this year contributed to the increased
occurrence of the disease, which is potentially a fatal flu-like
viral illness spread by mosquitoes breeding in artificial containers
and improperly managed garbage.
Dr. Chusak said, Dengue is a man-made problem related to human
behaviour and is affected by globalization, rapid unplanned and
unregulated urban development, poor water storage and unsatisfactory
sanitary conditions.
The hardest hit by the disease in Burma are the major cities
including Rangoon, Mandalay and Moulemine as these cities have
undergone rapid urbanization in the last few years.
--
Communicated by:
ProMED Rapporteur Joseph P. Dudley
[ProMED thanks Rapporteurs Mary Marshall and Brent Barrett for
sending similar reports.
A map of Burma can be accessed at:
<http://www.lib.utexas.edu/maps/middle_east_and_asia/burma_pol_96.jpg>
- Mod.TY]
